UML:TaggedValue.value: Relatively few of the scope codes defined in ISO19115 are relevant to CIM. I have therefore added a number of additional scope types - these are indicated with a trailing asterisk.
This would cover quality issues with the CIM itself
Locates the "target" of a CIM QualityIssue.
a description of the quality issue with reference to this specific feature
the type of feature that the quality issue refers too (for METAFOR this could be simulation, file, boundary condition etc.)
the reference to the specific feature (e.g. a URI to a file)

Records an issue with an instance of the CIM. The particular part of the instance being referred to is captured by the detail attribute(s). A resolution can be added to a quality issue. A single issue can have multiple subissues.
date (and time) issue was added to CIM
person/organisation responsible for identifying this quality issue
person/organisation allocated the responsibuility for addressing this issue
severity of issue (e.g. potential, minor, major etc. - enumeration list will need to be defined for METAFOR
current status of this issue (e.g. open, investigation, closed, etc. - enumeration values to be defined for METAFOR)
type of quality issue (e.g. metadata, data etc. - enumeration list needs to be defined for METAFOR
A description of what action was taken because of a quality issue.
description of resolution of quality issues - including external references if required
person/organisation responsible for resolution, or the person/organisation who should be contacted with any queries about the resolution of this quality issue

The starting point for a quality record. It can contain any number of issues and reports. An issue is an open-ended description of some issue about a CIM instance. A record is a prescribed description of some specific quantitative measure that has been applied to a CIM instance.
the specific data to which the quality information applies
The Document class shows all the attributes that a <<document>> stereotype should contain.
Contains the set of relationships supported by a Document.
Any class or feature with the <<document>> stereotype uses the attributes of this class. Furthermore, any class or feature with the <<document>> stereotype can form the root of an XML document.
a unique indentifier for this document - must be a GUID
The id of this document as referenced by an external body (ie: DOI, or even IPSL)
A contact for the author of this document (as opposed to the author of the artifact being described by this document; ie: the simulation or component or whatever).
Specifies the relationship of this document with another document. Various relationship types (depending on the type of document; ie: simulation, component, etc.) are supported.
a (set of) quality record(s) for this document.

A record of a document's history. A genealogy element contains a textual description and a set of relationships. Each relationship has a type and a reference to some target. There are different relationships for different document types.

A record of a relationship between one document and another. This class is abstract; specific document types must specialise this class for their relationshipTypes to be included in a document's genealogy.
This attribute is <<unused>>; it is a placeholder for specific relationshipTypes used by specialisations of Relationship.
note, changed quality attribute type from CIM_Quality to DQ_Element for now to remove circular imports between quality and shared.
A CIM-specific ResponsibleParty. Sub-classes the gmd ResponsibleParty type and adds the attribute "abbreviation."
The types of relationships that can be specified within a document's genealogy.
Describes a name given to an entity from a recognised standard. The CIM records the standard and the name. For example, the standard might be "CF" and the name might be "atmospheric_pressure".
this abstract class is part of the shared package; specialisations are located in other packages
